Soyone (ソヨネ) knew that her journey to Tokyo would likely be a one-way trip. She had made peace with that long ago.

Ten years—that’s how long it had been since her brother, Gōsuke (剛介), went missing. He had vanished along with a specialist team of scientists and military personnel who entered the Tokyo exclusion zone.

Now she stood on the decaying remains of the street where she and her brother had grown up. Her former home loomed ahead, unchanged except for the encroaching greenery slowly reclaiming the concrete metropolis.

Streetlights still glowed after all this time. But their flicker was more than nostalgic—it was a warning. She needed to find shelter soon. These old city streets were no safe haven for someone alone, let alone a well-supplied and armed team. Her childhood home might yet serve as a safe house for her expeditions deeper into the city.

They were once ordinary places—suburbs tucked between hills, where porch lights flickered on at dusk and children raced down quiet streets. But when the outbreak reached the outer districts, the silence became permanent.

Evacuation orders came fast. Families left behind meals still warm, laundry half-folded, and birthday decorations fluttering in the wind. The infected moved like a tide—slow at first, then relentless. Power grids failed. Communications went dark. The last broadcasts warned of containment breaches and urged citizens to flee inland.

Now, nature creeps back in. Ivy climbs the walls of empty homes. Birds nest in broken attics. The towns stand frozen in time, haunted not by screams—but by the absence of them. Survivors call them The Silent Towns, markers of a world that unraveled street by street.

Some say the infected still wander there, drawn to the echoes of memory. Others believe the towns are cursed, left untouched by scavengers and search teams alike. But one thing is certain: no one who returns stays long.

This commissioned artwork captures a lighthearted yet gentle scene between two characters standing together in their school uniforms. One figure carries a playful presence with bunny ears and a relaxed stance, while the other stands with composed confidence, exuding calm charm. The contrast between them feels natural, like two very different personalities who still share an easy bond.

I really enjoyed bringing this moment to life, and I love how it carries both warmth and a touch of humor. Since this is a commissioned piece, it means a lot to me to hear how it makes others feel too. Does it make you smile, or maybe remind you of a friendship of your own? I would love to hear your thoughts.
